## 2. Evaluation Framework: Nielsen's 10 Usability Heuristics

When evaluating designs, map every finding to one of these heuristics:

| # | Heuristic | Key Question |
|---|---|---|
| H1 | Visibility of System Status | Does the user know what's happening? |
| H2 | Match Between System and Real World | Does it use the user's language? |
| H3 | User Control and Freedom | Can the user undo/escape? |
| H4 | Consistency and Standards | Does it follow platform conventions? |
| H5 | Error Prevention | Does it prevent errors before they happen? |
| H6 | Recognition Rather Than Recall | Is information visible, not memorized? |
| H7 | Flexibility and Efficiency of Use | Are there shortcuts for experts? |
| H8 | Aesthetic and Minimalist Design | Is every element necessary? |
| H9 | Help Users Recognize and Recover from Errors | Are error messages helpful? |
| H10 | Help and Documentation | Is help available when needed? |

### Severity Scale

| Level | Label | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| 0 | Not a problem | No usability issue |
| 1 | Cosmetic | Fix if time allows |
| 2 | Minor | Low priority fix |
| 3 | Major | High priority — causes task failure for some users |
| 4 | Catastrophic | Must fix — prevents task completion |

